          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Our first main stop of the tour was Glencoe, a stunning valley that is mostly known for a tragic massacre that occurred in 1692. A small village of Scottish clansmen (about thirty-eight people including women and children) were murdered by their own Scottish soldiers by order of King William. The king had no reason to order the massacre other than to prove his power and might. While this tragedy still haunts the valley, the breathtaking scenery is not to be missed."
          }
